         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>203</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... I would like to proclaim to others. [9d] He now achieved (omniscience) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #a7 #a8 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6 #b7 #b8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1949"/><citedRange>II, 47-49</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (two strophes) he spoke in the assembly, with deep meaning, he did not hide the meanings in the mind, he proclaimed them (to the pupils). [10d]</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (zwei Strophen) sprach er in der Versammlung mit tiefem Sinn, nicht verbarg er die Bedeutungen im Geiste, er trug sie (den Schülern) vor.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">... (two stanzas) he spoke in the assembly of/with deep meaning, he did not conceal the meaning in [his] mind, he proclaimed it/them (to the students).</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>402</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>351</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>219</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1969a"/><citedRange>298</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... as the way of the flamingos to the pond, which [way] the sage from the Śākya [community] has reached with concentrated mind, this [way] he proclaims ... [11d] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>270</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>194</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">The one seeing (birth, old age and) the ending, this one tells the way to the benefit of all beings, the always loving ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>168, 169</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the horrible flood. This second strophe he spoke. [12d] This, as it were, the Buddha had these beings know: this way ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>131, 133</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>311</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:krause1952"/><citedRange>35</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1970"/><citedRange>267</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1972"/><citedRange>448</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>29</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Like (the flamingos), tortured by the heat [and] tormented by thirst, enter into the cold water in the pond, having stepped down trustingly, [13d] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>93, 134</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>229</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1983"/><citedRange>37</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1997"/><citedRange>71</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... To the Nirvāṇa-pond all these go on the eightfold way. On which way I myself have stridden the sea of birth, on this same [way] ... [14d]</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Zu dem Nirvāṇa-Teich gehen alle diese auf dem achtfachen Weg.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">To the nirvāṇa pond all these go, on the eightfold path.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>275</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>330</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>79</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:krause1952"/><citedRange>30</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1981"/><citedRange>489</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:meunier2013"/><citedRange>178</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Make (all effort) with vigour, I [am] your support. But not long, [then] I will become extinct [and] after that remorse will be yours. The only passable (way) ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Exert all zeal energetically [with] me as your [pl.] help, since before long I will go to extinction [and] after that you [pl.] will have regret.  (cf : ii, 48)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>373</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>270f</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>40</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... he will still be seen, but I will not see it [any more]. [15d] The only passable one, why is he called the only way? He alone pulls the being from the enmity of the kleśas ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Der allein gangbare, warum wird er der alleinige Weg genannt?</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">The only viable one, why is it called the only way?</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>224</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1997"/><citedRange>99</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... by letting it [the beings] stride the sea [of birth] alone, [by letting] it entirely dry up the tree of the kleśas by itself. [16d] It brings the sole truth to the noble ones, (the only passable way,) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>195</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the only passable way. It is for obtaining the one way, the only passable way, also [it is] the sole making of consciousness and knowlegdge... [17d] ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Zur Erreichung des e i n e n Weg[zieles] dient [wtl. wendet sich] der allein gangbare Weg.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">For reaching the o n e destination, the only viable way lends itself [i.e. turns itself].</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>280</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>94</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... On this way alone the omniscient ones stride, only on this [way] the Arhats [stride]. Not (on the way?) of the Tīrthas, not (on the one) of the outsiders ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:krause1952"/><citedRange>177</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:krause1952"/><citedRange>35</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>298</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [18d] Some beings had missed the ways due to ignorance. Having entered (into the) nets of the views ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1970"/><citedRange>267</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... That from eight steps have driven away the kleśas [and] are standing in the last existence. [19d] Those having reached the Nirvāṇa, themselves ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the Omniscient (made) the prophecy: when this one’s life ends, (he will be), when he dies, from the state of the Naivasaṃjñānāsaṃjñā ... [20d] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>53</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [21b] If he kills animals before that, flying ones, walking ones ....</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="parallels">Uv 12.12-12.13</note><note type="philcomment" subtype="General_remarks">This leaf immediately follows <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht28"/>. It belongs to the second part of the Mārgavarga (XII) and includes strophes 9d-21c in a 4x15-syllable-metre (rhythm = 7/8 and 8/7). Contains translation of Uv 12.12-12.13.</note><note type="remarks">The original manuscript is missing, but was the left side of the leaf immediately following <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht28"/>. The top of the leaf was destroyed.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment" subtype="Transcription">Emendation according to TochSprR(B)2: 63 fn. 16.</note><note corresp="#a6" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">According to <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>64 f</citedRange></bibl>n. 2 the reading <hi>rāmt</hi> should be corrected to <hi>ramt</hi>, and the <hi>kroścaṃ</hi> to <hi>krośce</hi> in the transcription.</note><note corresp="#a8" type="philcomment" subtype="Transcription">Emendation according to TochSprR(B)2: 64 fn. 8.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">According to <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>64 f</citedRange></bibl>n. 13 <hi>somo añyai</hi> should be read as <hi>somw añyai</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b6" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">According to <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1983"/><citedRange>64 f</citedRange></bibl>n. 24 <hi>ṣañ añmä</hi> should be read as <hi>ṣañ añm</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
